In set theory, the assertion can be represented as follows:

Let Planet = {planets}
CelestialBody = {celestial bodies}
Star = {stars}

The statement can be rewritten as:

Planet subset of CelestialBody and CelestialBody intersect Star = not empty set. (By the rule of set theory: A intersect B = not (A union B'))
Planet intersect Star = not empty set.
Therefore some planets are stars.

The statement is false, since Planet intersect Star is an empty set. No planet is a star. 
So, the final answer is NO.
